<span id="freeTextContainer13659737463288626150">This had lots of fun stories about growing up in the south. I really enjoyed the one about her watching scary movies and then being afraid to do anything at home. I can relate to that!<br/><br/>My favorite was when she was talking about her first grade class, and how they couldn&apos;t go on a field trip to the reptile center because of budget cuts. So she gets a snake from her house and brings it to school. In the process, they have to ice the snake to calm him down, he gets loose in the room, and it bites he</span>
  <span id="freeText13659737463288626150" style="display:none">This had lots of fun stories about growing up in the south. I really enjoyed the one about her watching scary movies and then being afraid to do anything at home. I can relate to that!<br /><br />My favorite was when she was talking about her first grade class, and how they couldn't go on a field trip to the reptile center because of budget cuts. So she gets a snake from her house and brings it to school. In the process, they have to ice the snake to calm him down, he gets loose in the room, and it bites her. She said "And that night, keeping my throbbing hand elevated while infection slowly set in, I read my students' writing and realized that they had learned more about snakes from my bumbling demonstration than my classes in other years had ever learned from the smooth reptile demonstration... In the end, I have to admit that these budget cuts may make better teachers of us all. At least, those of us who survive." p. 216<br /><br />I had to laugh at that quote, because I know all about creative teaching during tight times.</span>
